               <head>CLEMENT OF LANTHONY, IACOPO DA VARAZZE; S. XV </head>
               <msContents>
                  <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <p>
                     <secFol><locus>(f. 2)</locus> Quando</secFol>
                     <secFol><locus>(f. 80)</locus> perdicioni</secFol>
                  </p>
                  <p>Two originally separate volumes, put together at an unknown date, perhaps after 1600.</p>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="perg">
                        <support>Parchment</support>
                        <extent>180 leaves (ii + 178) <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>220</height>
                              <width>160</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <note>Heavily retrimmed, affecting running heads and marginalia, the edges spattered with red.</note>
                        </extent>
                        <collation>1–8<hi rend="superscript">8</hi>, 9<hi rend="superscript">6</hi>, 10<hi rend="superscript">8</hi> / 11–17<hi rend="superscript">8</hi>, 18<hi rend="superscript">10</hi>, 19–22<hi rend="superscript">8</hi>; catchwords in I, and quire-signatures of the form ‘i. qª. i’, ‘i. qª. ii’ etc., mainly cropped; framed catchwords in II. </collation>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding calendar="Gregorian" notAfter="1700" notBefore="1600">
                        <p>Standard Merton s. xvii, sewn on four bands; formerly chained from the usual position. Fols. i-ii, 177–8 are paper binding leaves, fols. i and 178 from the same printed book as in MS 84.</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <provenance>John Bale (Appendix C, no. 7) saw at least part I at Merton. James, no. 167, specifies part II only, so the two parts may only have been united after 1600. Inside the front cover is a sheet of paper with ‘F. 4, 9’ (canc.) and a table of contents, s. xvii, ‘P. 3. 7. Art:’, s. xvii, canc. and replaced with ‘C. 1. 15 (CCXL)’ in red; the College bookplate.</provenance>
               </history>
